281. Grande operae pretium] This is a common expression. See ix. 28, xii. 127, and vi. 474, n. As to ‘follis' see xiii. 61, n. ‘Aluta’ is prepared leather. In vii. 192 it is used for a shoe. Here it means a leathern purse and ‘tumida' like ‘ tenso’ means that it is well filled. The name is from ‘alumen’ (alum), in which it was steeped to soften it. So we are told in Dict. 284. Non unus mentes ayz'tat furora] He goes back to what he said in v. 136, that avarice is madness. Some are mad one way and some another. Orestes was driven mad by the Erinnyes of his mother, and Ajax was mad when he flogged the beasts and thought he was listening to the eries of Agamemnon and Ulysses.
